Ranunculus sceleratus is a species of flowering plant in the buttercup family.
It is commonly known as cursed buttercup, bristly buttercup, or celery-leaved buttercup.
This plant typically grows in wetlands, marshes, and on the edges of streams and ponds.
The stems of Ranunculus sceleratus are ribbed, and the leaves are deeply-cut with a round or kidney-shaped outline.
It is a perennial herbaceous plant that can reach up to 90 centimeters in height.
The flowers of Ranunculus sceleratus are small and yellow, with five shiny petals.
Its seeds are small, oval-shaped, and brown in color.
